---
import CodeBlock from "../../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

const brewInstall = `brew install shivamhwp/tap/wrec-cli     # CLI for terminals, scripts, agents
brew install --cask shivamhwp/tap/wrec  # the app`;

const curlInstall = `curl -fsSL https://wrec.app/install | sh`;

const quarantine = `xattr -dr com.apple.quarantine /Applications/Wrec.app`;

const runFromSource = `cargo build -p daemon --bin daemon   # optional, makes first start faster
cargo run -p app                     # the GPUI app
cargo run -p cli -- targets --json   # the CLI`;
---

<DocsLayout title="wrec docs" current="docs">
  <h1>wrec docs</h1>
  <p>The most efficient screen recorder for mac.</p>
  <p>
    Wrec records displays or windows with a native ScreenCaptureKit pipeline,
    writes hardware-encoded <code>.mov</code> files, and gives you both a small GPUI
    app and a JSON-friendly <code>wrec</code> CLI built for scripts and coding agents.
  </p>
  <p>
    Automating wrec? The <a href="/docs/agents">agent docs</a> are the operating contract.
    Curious how it works? See
    <a href="/docs/architecture">architecture</a> and
    <a href="/docs/configuration">configuration</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>The flow</h2>
  <ol class="flow-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Pick a target</strong> — <code>wrec targets --json</code> lists displays
      and windows. The app shows the same list.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Submit a job</strong> — the app or CLI sends the recording job to a
      local daemon over a Unix socket. One job records at a time; extras queue.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Capture</strong> — the daemon spawns a native capture engine (ScreenCaptureKit
      → AVAssetWriter) that writes a hardware-encoded
      <code>.mov</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Control the job</strong> — pause, resume, stop, or cancel from either
      client. Every state change streams as a JSON job event.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Collect the file</strong> — recordings land in
      <code>~/Movies/&lt;app name&gt;</code>. History and metrics go to SQLite,
      kept separate from the media files.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Install</h2>
  <p>Both the app and the CLI are on Homebrew:</p>
  <CodeBlock code={brewInstall} label="Copy install commands" />
  <p>The standalone CLI can also be installed with:</p>
  <CodeBlock code={curlInstall} label="Copy install command" />
  <p>
    The app is also downloadable from
    <a
      href="https://github.com/shivamhwp/wrec/releases"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub Releases</a
    >. Release builds are not notarized yet, so macOS blocks the first launch of
    the app. Clear the quarantine recursively and reopen:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={quarantine} label="Copy command" />

  <h2>Requirements</h2>
  <ul class="flow-list">
    <li>
      <strong>macOS 15+</strong> — Apple Silicon is the primary target.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Screen Recording permission</strong> — for the app, or for the terminal
      running the CLI.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Audio Recording permission</strong> — only when system audio capture
      is enabled.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Run it from source</h2>
  <CodeBlock code={runFromSource} label="Copy commands" />
  <p>
    Requires full Xcode (for GPUI shader compilation and the Swift capture
    engine). See
    <a
      href="https://github.com/shivamhwp/wrec/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer">CONTRIBUTING.md</a
    > for the full development setup.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
